    "id": "Ugy1CsIji7CJTKDqTrF4AaABAg",
    "author": "@rowanarmitage79",
    "author_channel_id": "UCpd8yXz2MZkmK9B3Ij0Ilng",
    "text": "This made me think (It didn’t hurt as much as I was expecting) from position 0 (absolute 90°) on the large orange disc, we move to 108° (90+18) the cam will have to rotate more than 180° to be at BDC, with reference to the axis of the large orange disc. Specifically the smaller disc would have to rotated 198° for tangents of both discs to be perpendicular to a line drawn between both axis’s. I hope I’ve explained that adequately.\nRegards\nRowan",
    "likes": 0,
    "published_at": "2024-11-16T03:57:29Z",
    "reply_count": 1,
    "replies": [
      {
        "id": "Ugy1CsIji7CJTKDqTrF4AaABAg.AAtFuIub6wSAAyvqnXst6k",
        "author": "@ThinkingandTinkering",
        "author_channel_id": "UC4AkVj-qnJxNtKuz3rkq16A",
        "text": "no mate the line isn't drawn yet - you are drawing the line so you fix the rotation of the smaller cam to 180 - it will then trace the path - i you fix the angle of rotation at 198 the path will be too long",
        "likes": 1,
        "published_at": "2024-11-18T08:48:57Z"
      }
    ]
  },
